      "strengths_deep_dive": [
        "EJI's operational model is characterized by extreme leaness and high accountability. The organization holds a <cite id=\"13\">Gold Seal of Transparency from Candid</cite> and a <cite id=\"14\">perfect 100 Leadership score</cite> from Charity Navigator. Financially, the organization is an outlier in its peer group; while the <cite id=\"15\">peer program ratio median is 88.2%</cite>, EJI directs <cite id=\"4\">96.9% of its expenses to programs</cite>. This efficiency is paired with significant grantmaking, including <cite id=\"16\">$50,375,000 in total grants</cite> to domestic partners like the Legacy Foundation to further racial justice initiatives."
      ],
      "summary": "The Equal Justice Initiative (EJI) is a Montgomery-based legal advocacy organization <cite id=\"1\">founded in 1989</cite> that provides critical representation to the poor, the incarcerated, and individuals <cite id=\"2\">facing execution or extreme punishment</cite>. Operating with a <cite id=\"3\">97/100 overall score from Charity Navigator</cite>, EJI maintains an <cite id=\"4\">exceptional 96.9% program expense ratio</cite>, ensuring that every dollar contributed directly fuels its mission to challenge racial and economic injustice. In the 2023 fiscal year, the organization reported <cite id=\"5\">$67,268,484 in total revenue</cite>, supported largely by <cite id=\"6\">$59.9 million in public contributions</cite>. Beyond the courtroom, EJI has expanded its impact through public education and community services, recently <cite id=\"7\">launching a mobile grocery</cite> and providing support to <cite id=\"8\">7,200 families</cite>. Their legal work remains prolific, having secured <cite id=\"9\">37 death row commutations</cite> and awarding <cite id=\"10\">$370,000 in scholarship funds</cite> to support affected communities.",
